	<clause id="_introduction" obligation="normative"><title>Introduction</title><clause id="_its_90_definition" obligation="normative"><title>ITS-90 Definition</title><p id="_8eb153fe-889e-462a-b992-c85192ea32a5">Above the freezing point of silver, <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>1234.93</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> (<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>961.78</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mrow><mi>°</mi><mi>C</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></stem>), the temperature <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> is, according to the definition of the ITS-90, defined by the equation</p>
	<formula id="eq1">
	<stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>L</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>λ</mi></mstyle></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>L</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>λ</mi></mstyle></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>X</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi>exp</mi><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>λ</mi></mstyle><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>X</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>exp</mi><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>λ</mi></mstyle><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mi>,</mi></math></stem>
	</formula>
	<p id="_f111203a-339c-47a4-8f70-fcd656389c9f">where <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>X</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></math></stem> refers to the silver <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced open="{" close="}"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mtext>Ag</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1234.93</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></math></stem>, the gold <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced open="{" close="}"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mtext>Au</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1337.33</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></math></stem> or the copper <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced open="{" close="}"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mtext>Cu</mtext></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1357.77</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></math></stem> freezing points. <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>L</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>λ</mi></mstyle></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></stem> andare the spectral radiances of a blackbody at the wavelength <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>λ</mi></mstyle></math></stem> (in vacuo) at <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> and at <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>T</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow></msub><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>X</mi></mstyle></mrow></mfenced></math></stem>, respectively, and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0.014</mn><mn>388</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>m</mi></mstyle><mo>⋅</mo><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem><fn reference="1"><p id="_577ce403-8720-4cad-9656-916adc9a1645">Although the latest value of the second radiation constant, <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem>, differs from that in the original definition [<eref type="inline" bibitemid="Mohr2012" citeas="[24]">Mohr <em>et al.</em> 2012</eref>], the value of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>0.014388</mn><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>m</mi></mstyle><mtext> </mtext><mstyle mathvariant="normal"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></math></stem> fixed in the original text of the ITS-90 is to be used.</p></fn>.</p></clause>
